{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570136"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22694"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22694"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.08,0.06,0.53,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111555"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15641"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9160"},{"type":"tags","id":"9168"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45388"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111555"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of sudden onset severe central abdominal pain. The pain is constant, localised to the periumbilical region, and does not radiate. He feels nauseated and has vomited twice. He has no diarrhoea, no rectal bleeding, and has passed flatus earlier today.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Ten years ago he underwent a right hemicolectomy for colon cancer with no recurrence on follow-up. His regular medications are perindopril and metformin. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is retired and lives independently. He does not smoke and drinks several glasses of wine at weekends. There has been no recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. Pulse rate 92/min, blood pressure 134/86 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. His BMI is 30 kg/m2. The abdomen is rotund and generally soft with increased bowel sounds. There is focal periumbilical tenderness without obvious palpable mass or overlying skin changes. Digital rectal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal: venous lactate 1.7 mmol/L (0.5\u20132.0), C-reactive protein 18 mg/L (\u0026lt;5), white cell count 11.8 \u00d710^9/L (4.0\u201311.0). A contrast-enhanced CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adhesive small bowel obstruction","Recurrent malignant large bowel obstruction","Small bowel intussusception","Incarcerated para-umbilical hernia","Acute colonic pseudo-obstruction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOlder adults with acute localised periumbilical pain, vomiting and examination limited by a high body mass index may have an abdominal wall hernia that is not clinically obvious. Computed tomography is highly sensitive for identifying a bowel loop protruding through the linea alba at the umbilical region. An incarcerated hernia can present before overt obstruction, especially when only part of the bowel wall is trapped, and requires urgent surgical assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncarcerated para-umbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E is most consistent with a CT showing a knuckle of small bowel passing through a midline fascial defect at the umbilical region. The focal periumbilical tenderness, vomiting, prior abdominal surgery that does not anatomically explain a midline defect, and the absence of a distended, diffusely tender abdomen support a focal abdominal wall process. Incarceration can occur without early systemic instability and may precede complete obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdhesive small bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is plausible given prior laparotomy, but typically causes diffuse, cramping colicky pain, abdominal distension, and high-pitched tinkling bowel sounds with a transition point within the peritoneal cavity on imaging rather than at the abdominal wall. The stem emphasises focal periumbilical tenderness and a CT-demonstrated external knuckle, which argues against adhesions as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecurrent malignant large bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would usually present years after surgery with progressive constipation, distension, and vomiting if the obstruction is proximal enough, often with weight loss or constitutional symptoms. CT would more likely show mural thickening or an extrinsic mass with proximal colonic dilatation rather than a small bowel loop at an umbilical defect. Surveillance history of no recurrence further reduces likelihood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel intussusception\u003C/strong\u003E in adults is uncommon and often associated with a pathological lead point, presenting with intermittent colicky pain and sometimes gastrointestinal bleeding. CT classically shows a target or sausage-shaped mass within the lumen, not a loop traversing the anterior abdominal wall fascia. The focal periumbilical wall defect on imaging is more specific for a hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute colonic pseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E presents with massive colonic dilatation, abdominal distension, and discomfort in hospitalised or unwell individuals, often with precipitating factors such as severe illness, electrolyte disturbance, or medications. The clinical picture here is an acute focal pain with vomiting and a CT finding of a small bowel knuckle at the linea alba, which does not fit pseudo-obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A painful para-umbilical lump with vomiting and focal tenderness in an older person with obesity should raise concern for an incarcerated abdominal wall hernia.","Small bowel obstruction from adhesions usually presents with colicky pain, distension and high-pitched bowel sounds without a focal tender hernia.","Computed tomography demonstrating a knuckle of bowel at the linea alba confirms an incarcerated para-umbilical hernia and mandates urgent surgical assessment."],"references":["Murphy KP, O\u0027Connor OJ, Maher MM. Adult Abdominal Hernias. Am J Roentgenol. 2014; 202:W506-11.","Muysoms FE, Miserez M. Berrevoet F, et al. Classification of primary and incisional abdominal wall hernias. Hernia 2009; 13:407\u2013414","Knipe H, Ranchod A, Ashraf A, et al. Paraumbilical hernia. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 16 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-32160"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22694"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22042"},{"type":"media","id":"22043"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22042"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JbqzypG8PLmIXSd9pwLQH1dBhN52B7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JbqzypG8PLmIXSd9pwLQH1dBhN52B7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":693,"height":702}},{"type":"media","id":"22043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22043"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qCFeWojg2AIUdKlDuRwPKzfm6uZeRK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qCFeWojg2AIUdKlDuRwPKzfm6uZeRK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":825,"height":741}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93644"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-16T21:09:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T21:10:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15641"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111555"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id